Phase 1 — Instrumentation Architecture
Alloy Topology Decision
Given VMs + AKS, you need a tiered Alloy topology:
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    LGTM Stack (other team)               │
│         Mimir │ Loki │ Tempo │ Grafana Enterprise        │
└──────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────┘
                       │  OTLP/remote_write
          ┌────────────┴────────────┐
          │                         │
┌─────────▼──────────┐   ┌─────────▼──────────┐
│  Alloy Aggregator   │   │  Alloy on AKS       │
│  (dedicated VM)     │   │  (DaemonSet)        │
│  - Batching         │   │  - GitLab k8s comps │
│  - Relabeling       │   │  - Kubernetes meta  │
│  - Auth to LGTM     │   └────────────────────┘
└─────────┬──────────┘
          │
  ┌───────┴────────┐
  │                │
┌─▼──────┐   ┌────▼────┐
│Alloy   │   │Alloy    │
│Nexus   │   │GitLab   │
│VM fleet│   │VMs      │
└────────┘   └─────────┘
Why an aggregator? You don't want every VM having credentials to push directly to the LGTM stack. The aggregator handles auth, batching, and gives you a choke point for cardinality control — critical since you said LGTM is managed by another team (you don't want to cause their Mimir bill to explode).
Alloy Config Skeleton — Nexus VM
// alloy/nexus.alloy

// ============================================
// METRICS — Nexus Prometheus endpoint
// ============================================
prometheus.scrape "nexus_metrics" {
  targets = [{
    __address__ = "localhost:8081",
    __metrics_path__ = "/service/metrics/prometheus",
    instance = env("HOSTNAME"),
    job = "nexus",
    environment = env("ENVIRONMENT"),   // prod/staging
    region = env("AZURE_REGION"),
  }]
  scrape_interval = "30s"
  bearer_token = env("NEXUS_METRICS_TOKEN")
  
  forward_to = [prometheus.relabel.nexus_drop_noise.receiver]
}

// Drop high-cardinality noise before it leaves the VM
prometheus.relabel "nexus_drop_noise" {
  rule {
    // Drop per-repository byte histograms at scrape level
    // (aggregate at query time instead)
    source_labels = ["__name__"]
    regex = "nexus_repository_.*_bytes_bucket"
    action = "drop"
  }
  rule {
    // Normalize repository names to prevent cardinality explosion
    source_labels = ["repository_name"]
    target_label = "repository_name"
    regex = "(.*)-[0-9a-f]{8}-[0-9a-f]{4}.*"  // strip UUID suffixes
    replacement = "${1}-ephemeral"
  }
  forward_to = [prometheus.remote_write.aggregator.receiver]
}

// ============================================
// LOGS — Nexus log files
// ============================================
loki.source.file "nexus_logs" {
  targets = [
    {
      __path__ = "/opt/sonatype-work/nexus3/log/nexus.log",
      job = "nexus",
      log_type = "application",
    },
    {
      __path__ = "/opt/sonatype-work/nexus3/log/request.log",
      job = "nexus",
      log_type = "access",
    },
    {
      __path__ = "/opt/sonatype-work/nexus3/log/audit.log", 
      job = "nexus",
      log_type = "audit",
    },
  ]
  forward_to = [loki.process.nexus_parse.receiver]
}

loki.process "nexus_parse" {
  // Parse access log for SLI extraction via log-based metrics
  stage.regex {
    expression = `(?P<method>\w+) (?P<path>[^\s]+) HTTP/[\d\.]+ (?P<status>\d+) (?P<bytes>\d+) (?P<duration_ms>\d+)`
  }
  stage.labels {
    values = {
      method = "method",
      status_class = "",   // derived below
      repository = "",     // extracted from path
    }
  }
  stage.template {
    source = "status_class"
    template = "{{ if lt .status 400 }}2xx{{ else if lt .status 500 }}4xx{{ else }}5xx{{ end }}"
  }
  // Extract repository from path: /repository/<repo-name>/...
  stage.regex {
    source = "path"
    expression = `^/repository/(?P<repository>[^/]+)`
  }
  stage.metrics {
    metric.counter {
      name = "nexus_requests_total"
      description = "Total Nexus HTTP requests extracted from access log"
      source = "status_class"
      config = { action = "inc" }
    }
    metric.histogram {
      name = "nexus_request_duration_ms"
      description = "Nexus request duration from access log"
      source = "duration_ms"
      config = {
        buckets = [10, 50, 100, 250, 500, 1000, 2500, 5000]
      }
    }
  }
  forward_to = [loki.write.aggregator.receiver]
}

// ============================================
// TRACES — OTLP receiver (if Nexus emits any)
// ============================================
otelcol.receiver.otlp "nexus_traces" {
  grpc { endpoint = "0.0.0.0:4317" }
  http { endpoint = "0.0.0.0:4318" }
  output {
    traces = [otelcol.exporter.otlp.aggregator.input]
  }
}

// ============================================
// HOST METRICS — VM-level signals
// ============================================
prometheus.exporter.unix "node" {
  // Key collectors for a Java app on a VM
  enable_collectors = [
    "cpu", "diskstats", "filesystem", 
    "loadavg", "meminfo", "netdev",
    "netstat", "stat", "time",
    "uname", "vmstat",
  ]
}
prometheus.scrape "node_metrics" {
  targets = prometheus.exporter.unix.node.targets
  scrape_interval = "15s"
  forward_to = [prometheus.remote_write.aggregator.receiver]
}

// ============================================  
// JVM METRICS — via JMX exporter sidecar
// ============================================
prometheus.scrape "jvm_metrics" {
  targets = [{ __address__ = "localhost:9010", job = "nexus-jvm" }]
  scrape_interval = "30s"
  forward_to = [prometheus.remote_write.aggregator.receiver]
}

// ============================================
// OUTPUTS
// ============================================
prometheus.remote_write "aggregator" {
  endpoint {
    url = env("ALLOY_AGGREGATOR_URL") + "/api/v1/push"
  }
}
loki.write "aggregator" {
  endpoint {
    url = env("ALLOY_AGGREGATOR_URL") + "/loki/api/v1/push"
  }
}
otelcol.exporter.otlp "aggregator" {
  client {
    endpoint = env("ALLOY_AGGREGATOR_OTLP_ENDPOINT")
  }
}
Phase 2 — SLI / SLO / SLA Framework
This is where most teams get it wrong by starting with SLOs before defining what "working" actually means to users.
The Right Mental Order
User Journey → Failure Modes → SLIs → SLOs → Error Budget → SLA
Nexus — User Journeys and SLIs
Who uses Nexus? CI/CD pipelines pulling artifacts and developers/pipelines pushing artifacts. Their experience is binary: the pipeline works or it doesn't.
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ NEXUS SLI FRAMEWORK                                              │
├──────────────┬──────────────────────┬───────────────────────────┤
│ Dimension    │ SLI Definition       │ PromQL                    │
├──────────────┼──────────────────────┼───────────────────────────┤
│ AVAILABILITY │ % of 1min windows    │ See below                 │
│              │ where Nexus health   │                           │
│              │ endpoint returns 200 │                           │
├──────────────┼──────────────────────┼───────────────────────────┤
│ LATENCY      │ % of artifact pulls  │ See below                 │
│              │ completing < 2s      │                           │
│              │ (p95 threshold)      │                           │
├──────────────┼──────────────────────┼───────────────────────────┤
│ ERROR RATE   │ % of requests that   │ See below                 │
│              │ are non-5xx          │                           │
├──────────────┼──────────────────────┼───────────────────────────┤
│ CORRECTNESS  │ % of checksums that  │ Log-based metric          │
│              │ validate on pull     │                           │
└──────────────┴──────────────────────┴───────────────────────────┘
PromQL for Nexus SLIs:
# rules/nexus-sli.yaml

groups:
  - name: nexus.sli
    interval: 30s
    rules:

      # --- AVAILABILITY SLI ---
      # Good: health check succeeds
      - record: sli:nexus_availability:ratio_rate5m
        expr: |
          avg_over_time(
            probe_success{job="blackbox", target=~".*nexus.*health.*"}[5m]
          )

      # --- LATENCY SLI ---
      # Good requests: GET /repository/* completing under 2000ms
      - record: sli:nexus_latency_good:rate5m
        expr: |
          sum(rate(
            nexus_request_duration_ms_bucket{
              le="2000",
              method="GET",
              path=~"/repository/.*"
            }[5m]
          ))

      - record: sli:nexus_latency_total:rate5m
        expr: |
          sum(rate(
            nexus_request_duration_ms_count{
              method="GET",
              path=~"/repository/.*"
            }[5m]
          ))

      - record: sli:nexus_latency:ratio_rate5m
        expr: |
          sli:nexus_latency_good:rate5m 
            / 
          sli:nexus_latency_total:rate5m

      # --- ERROR RATE SLI ---
      - record: sli:nexus_errors_good:rate5m
        expr: |
          sum(rate(nexus_requests_total{status_class!="5xx"}[5m]))

      - record: sli:nexus_errors_total:rate5m
        expr: |
          sum(rate(nexus_requests_total[5m]))

      - record: sli:nexus_error_rate:ratio_rate5m
        expr: |
          sli:nexus_errors_good:rate5m 
            / 
          sli:nexus_errors_total:rate5m

      # --- COMPOSITE SLI (for a single "is Nexus working?" signal) ---
      - record: sli:nexus_composite:ratio_rate5m
        expr: |
          min(
            sli:nexus_availability:ratio_rate5m,
            sli:nexus_latency:ratio_rate5m,
            sli:nexus_error_rate:ratio_rate5m
          )
SLO Targets and Error Budgets:
# Nexus — Tier 1 platform service
# Used by ALL CI/CD pipelines → very high availability target

nexus_slos:
  availability:
    target: 99.9%           # 43.8 min/month error budget
    window: 30d
    rationale: >
      Nexus outage = all pipelines broken. Even 30min outage 
      is significant org-wide impact.
  
  latency_p95_pull:
    target: 99.0%           # 7.2 hours/month
    threshold: 2000ms
    rationale: >
      Artifact pulls happen in critical path of CI. 
      2s threshold covers even large Docker layers over internal network.
  
  error_rate:
    target: 99.5%
    rationale: >
      0.5% error budget accounts for transient proxy errors,
      auth token rotation windows, and rolling restarts.

# SLA (what you commit to consumers — slightly softer than SLO)
nexus_sla:
  availability: 99.5%       # gives you headroom vs 99.9% SLO
  support_response:
    p1_outage: 15min
    p2_degraded: 1hr
GitLab — More Complex, Component-Level SLIs
GitLab has multiple tiers — you need SLIs per component because failure modes are different:
GitLab Service Map:
  Webservice (AKS)    → handles web UI + API
  Sidekiq (AKS)       → async job processing (pipelines, notifications)
  Gitaly (VMs)        → Git operations (the really critical one)
  Registry (AKS/VM)   → container image push/pull
  PostgreSQL (VM)      → primary datastore
  Redis (VM)          → caching + job queue
# Gitaly SLI — most critical, git operations
- record: sli:gitaly_latency:ratio_rate5m
  expr: |
    sum(rate(
      gitaly_service_client_requests_total{
        grpc_code="OK"
      }[5m]
    )) 
    / 
    sum(rate(gitaly_service_client_requests_total[5m]))

# Pipeline throughput SLI — are jobs actually running?
- record: sli:gitlab_pipeline_success:ratio_rate1h
  expr: |
    sum(rate(
      gitlab_ci_pipeline_duration_seconds_count{
        status="success"
      }[1h]
    ))
    /
    sum(rate(
      gitlab_ci_pipeline_duration_seconds_count{
        status=~"success|failed"
      }[1h]
    ))
