Phase 6 — What You Might Have Missed
A few things that often get overlooked:
Synthetic monitoring — Blackbox probing from outside the VMs. Don't just instrument from within; probe Nexus's /service/rest/v1/status and GitLab's /-/health from an Alloy instance in a different network zone. This catches network-level failures your internal metrics won't see.
Cardinality governance — Since LGTM is managed by another team, you need a cardinality budget agreement upfront. Instrument Alloy itself: alloy_prometheus_remote_storage_samples_total and set up a dashboard showing your cardinality growth. This is the #1 cause of friction with shared observability platforms.
Change correlation — Wire GitLab's deployment events (via webhook → Loki) so your dashboards show deployment markers. When a graph spikes, you immediately see if a deployment caused it.
Runbook links in alerts — Every alert annotation should have a runbook_url. Use GHCP to draft the initial runbooks from your alert definitions: "Write a runbook for this alert. Include: what it means, how to verify, 5 investigation steps, and escalation path."
Data retention tiers — Agree with the LGTM team on: raw metrics at 15s for 15 days, downsampled 5m for 90 days, 1h for 2 years. This affects SLO reporting dashboards significantly.
GitLab → Nexus dependency tracing — If you instrument both with OTLP traces, you can get traces that show a CI job → Nexus artifact pull as a single trace. This is high value for diagnosing "why is my pipeline slow" and requires coordinating trace context propagation via HTTP headers between GitLab runners and Nexus — something you've already explored with the TRACEPARENT work.
